{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01M3gBQWumeRFm9T72c9YyTD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01UNqQHkdKqsGxHo5eQcqf3K","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"STORY_CONTENT=$(cat /tmp/codeharness-verify-9-5-multi-stack-docs-remaining-consumers/story.md)\n\ncat > /tmp/codeharness-verify-9-5-multi-stack-docs-remaining-consumers/verify-prompt.txt << 'PROMPT_EOF'\nYou are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The `src/` directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading `README.md` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file `story.md` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Read it now.\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n4. For ACs that involve Claude Code sessions or agent workflows, use `docker exec codeharness-verify claude ...` to spawn real sessions inside the container\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: `codeharness-verify`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness init --json`\n\nThe container has the following tools installed:\n- `codeharness` — the project CLI\n- `claude` — Claude Code CLI (authenticated via ANTHROPIC_API_KEY env var)\n- `curl`, `jq` — for querying observability endpoints\n- `showboat` — for proof document validation\n- `node`, `npm` — Node.js runtime\n\n**IMPORTANT: When invoking `claude --print` inside Docker, always pass `--allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit` to prevent the nested session from hanging on tool permission prompts.**\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- `docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]`\n- Capture exit codes: `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): `http://localhost:9428`\n  - Example: `curl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&limit=10'`\n- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): `http://localhost:8428`\n  - Example: `curl 'http://localhost:8428/api/v1/query?query=up'`\n- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): `http://localhost:16686`\n  - Example: `curl 'http://localhost:16686/api/traces?service=codeharness-verify&limit=10'`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH `docker exec` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\n```bash\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n```\n\n- If the response contains **one or more log entries**, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains **zero log entries**, the code path is a silent gap.\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: `verification/9-5-multi-stack-docs-remaining-consumers-proof.md`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n```text\n## AC N: <description>\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n```\n\n```output\n<actual output>\n```\n\n**Verdict:** PASS | FAIL | [ESCALATE] (reason)\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use `bash` and `output` as code fence languages.** Never use bare ``` fences without a language tag. If quoting code snippets, use ```text. Showboat will try to execute any unlabeled code block.\n\n## VERIFICATION STRATEGY for this story\n\nThis story is about multi-stack support in docs scaffolding, readme template, verify/env detection, and teardown. All ACs test internal function behavior. To verify black-box:\n\n**AC1 (AGENTS.md multi-stack content):** Create a multi-stack project dir with package.json in frontend/ and Cargo.toml in backend/, then run `codeharness init` and check the generated AGENTS.md has per-stack sections.\n\n**AC2 (getStackLabel):** Already verified if AGENTS.md output uses \"Node.js (package.json) + Rust (Cargo.toml)\" label format.\n\n**AC3 (getProjectName):** Create project with both package.json and Cargo.toml, run init, check the project name in output.\n\n**AC4 (detectProjectType uses detectStacks):** Run `codeharness verify-env` in a multi-stack project and check it detects correctly.\n\n**AC5 (scaffoldDocs passes StackDetection[]):** Verified via AC1 — if AGENTS.md has per-stack sections, scaffoldDocs passed the array.\n\n**AC6 (README multi-stack install):** After init, check README.md has install commands for all stacks.\n\n**AC7 (teardown uses stacks array):** Run `codeharness teardown` in a project with multi-stack state and verify it handles nodejs cleanup.\n\n**AC8 (no regressions):** Run `docker exec codeharness-verify npm test` inside the container — but tests may not be installed. If not, verify by running `codeharness init` on a single-stack project and confirming it still works.\n\n**Key approach:** Create temp directories inside the container, populate them with package.json and Cargo.toml in subdirs, then run codeharness commands against them.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. **ALL commands MUST use `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`** — do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** — there is no `src/` directory in this workspace.\n3. **Report REAL failures** — if a feature does not work via the CLI, report as failure.\n4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** — reading docs alone is not evidence.\n5. **Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.**\n6. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** — infrastructure problems are NOT valid escalation reasons.\n7. **`claude` CLI is available** inside the container.\n8. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.**\nPROMPT_EOF\n\necho \"Prompt written: $(wc -l < /tmp/codeharness-verify-9-5-multi-stack-docs-remaining-consumers/verify-prompt.txt) lines\"","description":"Write verification prompt to file"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":126,"cache_read_input_tokens":67312,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":126},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e18f278-46ed-484a-b67e-63de3b199291","uuid":"4dc3ebf9-d732-4f45-b4b2-2c5fcf7b1fa4"}
