{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011uJegr2jyuH8cJvCc5N1MG","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Retrospective written to `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/epic-9-multi-stack-retrospective.md`.\n\n**Key findings:**\n\n- All 5 stories complete, 3,153 tests passing, 97.05% statement coverage, 88.56% branch coverage\n- Code review caught 11 HIGH-severity bugs across 4 of 5 stories -- the single most valuable quality gate\n- Story 9-2 had the most critical finds: data loss bugs where multi-stack state was never persisted to disk\n- Backward compatibility preserved cleanly via `Array.isArray()` runtime dispatch pattern across all stories\n- Two stories (9-4, 9-5) hit session time limits during verification -- recurring pattern\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Epic-level problems (recurring patterns):**\n- **Verification time crunch:** 2 of 5 stories exhausted session time before verification completed. This is not random -- implementation + code review consistently consume 85% of the time budget, leaving verification starved. This happened in stories 9-4 and 9-5.\n- **Story file status divergence:** All story files show `Status: verifying` while sprint-status.yaml shows `done`. Carried from every prior retrospective without resolution. The sync command exists but nobody runs it.\n- **LOW-severity issues accumulate without tracking:** 8+ LOW issues flagged across the epic but none tracked in a backlog. They exist only in session-issues.md prose. No mechanism to surface them in sprint planning.\n\n**Stories harder than expected and why:**\n- **9-2 (State schema migration):** 4 HIGH bugs found in code review. The difficulty was not the migration logic itself but ensuring all write paths (`writeState`, `recoverCorruptedState`, `init-project`) consistently persisted the new field. In-memory correctness did not guarantee on-disk correctness.\n- **9-3 (Init orchestrator):** The per-stack iteration loops looked trivial but produced dead code and double filesystem scans. Orchestrator refactors are deceptively hard because the side effects are spread across multiple modules.\n- **9-5 (Docs/remaining consumers):** `docs-scaffold.ts` grew to 295/300 lines. The 300-line ceiling created pressure to compress code rather than extract properly.\n\n**Action items needing immediate attention:**\n- **A1:** Extract helpers from `docs-scaffold.ts` (295/300 lines). Next feature addition will break the file size limit.\n- **A6:** Verification phase needs explicit time allocation. Two consecutive time-outs is a process failure, not bad luck.\n\n**Action items for backlog:**\n- A2: Wire `codeharness sync` into workflow (chronic carry)\n- A3: Remove dead `state.coverage.tools` write or add consumer\n- A4: Consolidate `getStackLabel()`/`stackDisplayName()` duplication\n- A5: Fix stale `detectStack` mock in verify-env tests\n\n**Process improvements that should be encoded in tooling/config:**\n- Story status sync should be automated in the verify step, not a manual command. The fact that `codeharness sync` exists but is never called means it needs to be wired into the `verify` sub-agent or post-verify hook.\n- LOW-severity issues from code review should be auto-written to a structured backlog file (not just session-issues.md prose) so sprint planning can surface them.\n- Session time budget should enforce a minimum 20% reservation for verification. If implementation + review exceeds 80%, the session should defer to a new session rather than rushing verification."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a2c13ff1cf5efec33 (use SendMessage with to: 'a2c13ff1cf5efec33' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 43049\ntool_uses: 22\nduration_ms: 163359</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e18f278-46ed-484a-b67e-63de3b199291","uuid":"094d1e61-78f7-4514-b894-c7b57dbf0c4e","timestamp":"2026-03-23T16:20:19.435Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /retrospective for Epic 9 (Multi-Stack Project Support). All stories are complete:\n- 9-1: Multi-stack detection with subdirectory scanning (done)\n- 9-2: State schema migration for multi-stack (done)\n- 9-3: Init orchestrator per-stack iteration (done)\n- 9-4: Multi-stage Dockerfile generation (done)\n- 9-5: Multi-stack docs and remaining consumers (done)\n\nSprint status file: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml\nSession issues log: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/.session-issues.md\n\nReview the epic's work, extract lessons learned, and produce the retrospective document. Read the session issues log for detailed sub-agent findings across all stories.\n\nDo NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Epic-level problems (recurring patterns across stories, process breakdowns)\n- Stories that were harder than expected and why\n- Action items that need immediate attention vs. backlog\n- Process improvements that should be encoded in tooling/config, not just documented\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a2c13ff1cf5efec33","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Retrospective written to `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/epic-9-multi-stack-retrospective.md`.\n\n**Key findings:**\n\n- All 5 stories complete, 3,153 tests passing, 97.05% statement coverage, 88.56% branch coverage\n- Code review caught 11 HIGH-severity bugs across 4 of 5 stories -- the single most valuable quality gate\n- Story 9-2 had the most critical finds: data loss bugs where multi-stack state was never persisted to disk\n- Backward compatibility preserved cleanly via `Array.isArray()` runtime dispatch pattern across all stories\n- Two stories (9-4, 9-5) hit session time limits during verification -- recurring pattern\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Epic-level problems (recurring patterns):**\n- **Verification time crunch:** 2 of 5 stories exhausted session time before verification completed. This is not random -- implementation + code review consistently consume 85% of the time budget, leaving verification starved. This happened in stories 9-4 and 9-5.\n- **Story file status divergence:** All story files show `Status: verifying` while sprint-status.yaml shows `done`. Carried from every prior retrospective without resolution. The sync command exists but nobody runs it.\n- **LOW-severity issues accumulate without tracking:** 8+ LOW issues flagged across the epic but none tracked in a backlog. They exist only in session-issues.md prose. No mechanism to surface them in sprint planning.\n\n**Stories harder than expected and why:**\n- **9-2 (State schema migration):** 4 HIGH bugs found in code review. The difficulty was not the migration logic itself but ensuring all write paths (`writeState`, `recoverCorruptedState`, `init-project`) consistently persisted the new field. In-memory correctness did not guarantee on-disk correctness.\n- **9-3 (Init orchestrator):** The per-stack iteration loops looked trivial but produced dead code and double filesystem scans. Orchestrator refactors are deceptively hard because the side effects are spread across multiple modules.\n- **9-5 (Docs/remaining consumers):** `docs-scaffold.ts` grew to 295/300 lines. The 300-line ceiling created pressure to compress code rather than extract properly.\n\n**Action items needing immediate attention:**\n- **A1:** Extract helpers from `docs-scaffold.ts` (295/300 lines). Next feature addition will break the file size limit.\n- **A6:** Verification phase needs explicit time allocation. Two consecutive time-outs is a process failure, not bad luck.\n\n**Action items for backlog:**\n- A2: Wire `codeharness sync` into workflow (chronic carry)\n- A3: Remove dead `state.coverage.tools` write or add consumer\n- A4: Consolidate `getStackLabel()`/`stackDisplayName()` duplication\n- A5: Fix stale `detectStack` mock in verify-env tests\n\n**Process improvements that should be encoded in tooling/config:**\n- Story status sync should be automated in the verify step, not a manual command. The fact that `codeharness sync` exists but is never called means it needs to be wired into the `verify` sub-agent or post-verify hook.\n- LOW-severity issues from code review should be auto-written to a structured backlog file (not just session-issues.md prose) so sprint planning can surface them.\n- Session time budget should enforce a minimum 20% reservation for verification. If implementation + review exceeds 80%, the session should defer to a new session rather than rushing verification."}],"totalDurationMs":163359,"totalTokens":43049,"totalToolUseCount":22,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3166,"cache_read_input_tokens":39038,"output_tokens":844,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3166},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
